So edh and math related, but didnt want to bring it up on twitter and hurt what anyone does.. but how do you math out reliably the % increase or decrease of Sol ring? 

Apparently someone did a study of 300 games and found a 4% decrease in wins playing sol ring (so less then 15)

When you do these sorts of experiments. How do you weed out everything else? Like the fact theres 3 people, 99 card decks, your hand, the cards you play in your hand. Your opponents hand. The cards THEY play, the cards you play to interact with what they play, the cards that another opponent plays to interact with another person aside you... etc?

Not trying to be mean. This isnt my field or anything, but in my probably ignorance... it just seems like a completely wild correlation, right?
I think the idea is that over a large enough number of games the other stuff will even out. But 300 doesn't seem like nearly enough for that.

Yeah... I dont know how many youd need, but at 300 it seems like a coincidence? I'm sure theres a whole thing I'm missing, but in edh especially with 3 other people alot of it seems like a chaotic mess of chance and situation.

Clearly at some point, things matter. Cedh decks exist. Some decks simply outshine others. So I'm sure theres something to crunching. I just dont know at what point its effective or just negligible(?)
That someone was likely the Command Zone, since that sounds about like the number of games they surveyed.
You don’t reliably gain that number from that small set of data. Anyone who parrots that episode they did is severely misguided and misusing statistics
Aka Kya your instinct here is correct

In statistics there's the concept of how confident (mathematically) a result can be. If the results are not even close (winner has most lands) then you don't need much data since the trend is strong and evident after small amounts of data. If the results are close (winner played sol ring) then u need more data before u can b confident.
Command zone said winner played sol ring, but they didnt have enough data to really say that.
Another way to say it is that they don’t have enough data to *disprove* the hypothesis’s opposite-case scenario. That’s a huge point in statistical analysis.
And when that was pointed out, josh kinda talked out his patootie
